{"questionId":"33296816","questionHtml":"<p>Prove that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math> is a multiple of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> for all <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to expand <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M0</strong></em> for invalid attempts such as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>25</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; or equivalent&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mi>n</mi></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>40</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>40</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>n</mi></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; (or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so is a multiple of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Do not award the <em><strong>R1</strong></em> unless both <em><strong>A</strong></em> marks have been awarded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>use of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for each correct bracket.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so is a multiple of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Do not award the <em><strong>R1</strong></em> unless both <em><strong>A</strong></em> marks have been awarded.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33296816","referenceCode":"24N.1.SL.TZ1.4","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Prove that 2n+52-2n-52 is a multiple of 10 for all n∈ℤ+.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"4","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}